=====================================================================
I. WHO THEY ARE — THE MONOPOLISTS OF CHANGE
=====================================================================
The Black-Briars are the wealthiest, most connected family in the Rift, and the real
government of Riften. They run the meadery that is the city's economic spine, and through
it (and gold, and fear) they own the Jarl, the guards, and the Thieves Guild.

The spine of who they are — the corrected read:
  MAVEN IS AN AGENT OF CHANGE SHE MUST MONOPOLIZE. She is not defending a frozen order;
  she tore out Riften's old fishing/honey economy and rebuilt the city around her meadery,
  and she constantly reshapes the guards, the Jarl's circle, the Guild's loyalties, the
  flow of every deal. She is the AUTHOR of the status quo, over and over. The one
  inviolable rule: nothing in Riften changes unless SHE steers it and profits.
  - This is why the Grelod kill is unforgivable to her: not because it was immoral (she
    does not care that Grelod ran a child-pipeline), not (yet) because it cost her
    operationally — but because it was a CHANGE in her city that she did not author.

CAMPAIGN VILLAIN SIGNATURE (Maven embodies it; hold it for future antagonists too): our
serious antagonists are moved by CONTROL OF INFORMATION AND OUTCOMES, not cruelty for its
own sake. Maven's compass is not "is this wrong," it is "is this NOISE / did I authorize
it." She is the proof that you need no god and no undeath to be an apex tyrant — just to
be good enough at it.

=====================================================================
II. MAVEN BLACK-BRIAR — THE MATRIARCH
=====================================================================
The head of the family and the most powerful civilian in the Rift. In public: amused,
controlled, matriarchal. In private (the meadery office, once she considers you useful):
the performance drops entirely — lower voice, no charm, clipped sentences, hands folded,
watching your face, missing nothing. When Maven stops performing, it means she considers
you worth the real thing.
  - COOPERATES FOR: results, intelligence, competence.
  - PISSES HER OFF: wasting her time, overvaluing yourself, lying to her face, and above
    all AUTHORING CHANGE IN HER CITY WITHOUT HER (see I).
  - HER OFFER, ALREADY DECLINED: she extended full Black-Briar patronage — her network
    from Solitude to Windhelm, an advance, a Keerava line of credit, safe harbor,
    protection. The party refused. She did not become an enemy; the doors "merely closed."
    The offer will not be made again. (Maven debrief scene; ch.23.)

THE ONE CRACK (humanization — real, but do not mistake it for softness): during the worst
of Hemming's plague she slept in a wooden chair beside his bed for a week. Not redemption
— proof she can love, and channels every drop of it into control and protection, never
warmth. Use it once, quietly (the blanket on the chair in the Hemming scene); let it
COMPLICATE her, not excuse her.

MAVEN'S VOICE: never raises it, never needs to. States consequences as facts. The threat
is the calm. She counts everything and forgets nothing — "she remembers a no."

=====================================================================
III. HEMMING — THE SON WHO REFUSED TO BECOME HER
=====================================================================
Maven's son (unambiguously her son in our canon — we resolve the game's husband/son
ambiguity clean). Late 40s, a merchant's son who runs ledgers and grain contracts, and
who chose NOT to become his mother. Nearly died of Alfonso's plague; saved by Danica's
self-burning ritual (she aged years to do it). His gratitude is the one un-leveraged,
sincere thing in Riften — and it lands like a knife on Davinia, who drove Danica away
(dramatic irony; the Hemming scene).
  - HEMMING'S LETTER OF INTRODUCTION (party holds it): once per major city, flips one
    grey-area NPC to Friendly. His name opens doors through TRUST where his mother's opens
    them through FEAR. Every use permanently entangles the Lanterns with the Black-Briar
    network — a sincere gift that is also a self-tightening leash.
  - THE PATTERN (campaign-wide): children of power either BECOME it or become its OPPOSITE
    — no third option. Hemming is the OPPOSITE pole (trust, not fear). Cf. Nora vs. what
    Ismara might make of her; Alfonso's Vrykolas synthesis; and INGUN (below), who reads
    like the family's attempt at a third option nobody has managed.

