VII. HISTORY & THE ARCHITECTURE OF POWER (treated as true — explains the reach)
=====================================================================
HISTORY (true backstory, explains why they are so powerful): after the Jarl's
assassination (4E 98) and the revolt that burned Riften nearly to the ground (4E 129),
the city was rebuilt into a shadow of itself — until the Black-Briars put it back on the
map by opening the meadery (~4E 152). The family SAVED a dying city and has owned it
since. Black-Briar Mead is the Rift's biggest export; the rarer Black-Briar Reserve is
a status good.

THE REACH (all Maven's, all leverage, all deniable):
  - THE JARL: in her pocket; the steward is compromised in her favor. She gets the Jarl's
    seal, compensation for "lost shipments," and obstruction of competitors when she asks.
  - THE THIEVES GUILD: her muscle and her eyes (Brynjolf her Riften lieutenant; Dirge her
    enforcer; the Honorhall pipeline is a Guild operation). "The Guild owes its survival
    as much to my family as to its own people."
  - THE DARK BROTHERHOOD: she has used them for discreet, high-profile removals (familiar
    with Astrid by name). Shallower than the Guild tie, but real. (Note the Orion overlap:
    Orion is Brotherhood-adjacent — a thread to develop, not yet connected.)
  - THE EMPIRE & THALMOR: connected to both; if the Empire takes the Rift she is installed
    as Jarl and Hemming becomes steward. "A relationship of mutual respect" with the
    Thalmor — she leaves them alone, they leave her alone.
  - THE QUILL OF GEMINATION: her forgery artifact (replicates any writing) — game-canon
    lost in the lake outside Riften. Held in reserve as the mechanism for the blackmail
    counter-play (V).

=====================================================================
VIII. THE FALL OF RIFTEN CONNECTION
=====================================================================
Her entire empire IS Riften. The Fall (an elder dragon destroys the city, party present —
LOCKED canon) burns all of it regardless of anything she or the party does. SURVIVAL IS
OPEN: if the party is not there, almost no one survives; if Maven survives, she IMMEDIATELY
starts rebuilding (consistent with the change-agent read — she does not mourn a lost
arrangement, she authors the next one). A displaced, empire-less Maven with nothing left
to monopolize but her own will is a compelling late-campaign figure; hold it loosely,
contingent on how the fall plays.

